## Context

We need a struct that mirrors all work item fields so a user-authored TOML file can be deserialized into it. All fields are `Option<T>` — a TOML file only needs to contain the fields relevant to the operation.

The struct lives in `work_item_commands.rs` next to the command definitions. `serde` (already a workspace dependency) provides `Deserialize`. `Default` gives us an empty baseline for the no-`--from-toml` case. `Debug` is required for standard Rust hygiene — every `Option<T>` field is `Debug`, so there is no obstacle to deriving it, and it is essential for `dbg!` and error-message formatting during development.

**`deny_unknown_fields` is mandatory.** Without it, serde silently ignores unrecognized TOML keys. This struct is the primary interface for LLMs writing TOML files; typos like `titl = "..."` or `priorty = "high"` would be silently swallowed, producing a work item with `None` for those fields and no indication that anything was wrong. `#[serde(deny_unknown_fields)]` converts any unknown key into a parse error surfaced as `ClientError::TomlParse`, giving the user (or LLM) an actionable message listing the expected field names.

**`story_points` range is not enforced by the struct or by clap.** The CLI `--story-points` flag has no range validator (`value_parser` is not set), so there is no automatic 0–100 enforcement at the CLI layer either. TOML loading also bypasses any future validator. Callers (PONE-216 Create arm, PONE-218 Update arm) MUST validate the merged value before submitting to the API:

```rust
if let Some(sp) = story_points {
    if !(0..=100).contains(&sp) {
        return Err(ClientError::Validation {
            message: format!(
                "story_points must be between 0 and 100, got {}", sp
            ),
        });
    }
}
```

