## Context

TOML has no null type. Work item responses regularly contain null fields (`assignee_id`, `sprint_id`, `parent_id`, `story_points`). The `toml` crate errors on nulls, so we strip them recursively before serialization.

TOML also requires all elements in an array to share the same type. If the serializer encounters a heterogeneous array (e.g., `["tag", 42]`), `toml::to_string_pretty` returns an error *after* the API call succeeded — the user sees a failure despite a working operation. To guard against this, heterogeneous arrays are normalized to `Vec<String>` by JSON-encoding each element.

The write happens **after** stdout receives the JSON response. JSON is always printed first, unconditionally — jq pipelines remain unaffected even if the file write fails.

All output-phase errors — TOML serialization failures, I/O write failures, JSON serialization failures — propagate as `ClientError` variants through a single `?`-based pipeline, surfacing at the same `eprintln!("Error: {}", e)` handler that handles command errors. No scattered `return ExitCode::FAILURE` branches.

