### 2. Add strip_nulls helper at bottom of file

This walks the entire `serde_json::Value` tree and drops any key whose value is `Null`. All other types pass through unchanged. Call this first, then pass the result to `homogenize_arrays`.

```rust
/// Recursively remove null values from a JSON structure.
///
/// TOML has no null type — the toml serializer errors on nulls.
/// This ensures every field written to a .toml file has a concrete value.
/// Null object values are filtered by key; null array elements are filtered by position.
fn strip_nulls(value: serde_json::Value) -> serde_json::Value {
    match value {
        serde_json::Value::Object(map) => serde_json::Value::Object(
            map.into_iter()
                .filter(|(_, v)| !v.is_null())
                .map(|(k, v)| (k, strip_nulls(v)))
                .collect(),
        ),
        serde_json::Value::Array(arr) => {
            serde_json::Value::Array(
                arr.into_iter()
                    .filter(|v| !v.is_null())
                    .map(strip_nulls)
                    .collect(),
            )
        }
        other => other,
    }
}
```

### 3. Add homogenize_arrays helper at bottom of file

TOML requires all elements in an array to share the same type. After nulls are stripped, any remaining heterogeneous array (e.g., `["label", 42]`) will cause `toml::to_string_pretty` to fail. This function normalizes such arrays by JSON-encoding every element as a string, producing a homogeneous `Vec<String>` that TOML can encode. Data is preserved — use `unwrap_or_else(|_| v.to_string())` so that a (theoretically impossible) serialization failure still produces the debug representation of the value rather than silently substituting an empty string.

`windows(2)` on a 0- or 1-element slice produces an empty iterator; `Iterator::all()` on an empty iterator returns `true` by contract. Therefore `is_homogeneous` is always `true` when `processed.len() <= 1` — a separate `|| processed.len() <= 1` guard is dead code and has been removed.

```rust
/// Returns true if two JSON values map to the same TOML type.
///
/// `std::mem::discriminant` is insufficient for `Value::Number` because
/// both integer and float share the `Number` variant. TOML distinguishes
/// integers from floats, so we use `is_f64()` to tell them apart.
fn same_toml_type(a: &serde_json::Value, b: &serde_json::Value) -> bool {
    use serde_json::Value;
    match (a, b) {
        (Value::Number(x), Value::Number(y)) => x.is_f64() == y.is_f64(),
        _ => std::mem::discriminant(a) == std::mem::discriminant(b),
    }
}
```

**Note on integer/float discrimination:** `std::mem::discriminant` compares `serde_json::Value` enum variants but cannot distinguish between integer and float `Number` values — both share the same `Number` variant. TOML treats integers and floats as distinct types, so a mixed-numeric array such as `[1, 2.5]` would pass the naïve discriminant check and then fail at `toml::to_string_pretty`. The `same_toml_type` helper uses `Number::is_f64()` to handle this case correctly.

```rust
/// Recursively ensure all JSON arrays are homogeneous (required by TOML spec).
///
/// TOML requires every element in an array to share the same type. If an array
/// contains mixed types after null-stripping, each element is serialized to its
/// JSON string representation, producing a homogeneous `Vec<String>` that the
/// toml crate can encode without error. Data is preserved in string form.
fn homogenize_arrays(value: serde_json::Value) -> serde_json::Value {
    match value {
        serde_json::Value::Object(map) => serde_json::Value::Object(
            map.into_iter()
                .map(|(k, v)| (k, homogenize_arrays(v)))
                .collect(),
        ),
        serde_json::Value::Array(arr) => {
            let processed: Vec<serde_json::Value> =
                arr.into_iter().map(homogenize_arrays).collect();
            let is_homogeneous = processed
                .windows(2)
                .all(|w| same_toml_type(&w[0], &w[1]));
            if is_homogeneous {
                serde_json::Value::Array(processed)
            } else {
                // Heterogeneous array: stringify each element as compact JSON.
                // unwrap_or_else preserves the debug form rather than silently
                // losing data if serialization ever fails.
                serde_json::Value::Array(
                    processed
                        .iter()
                        .map(|v| {
                            serde_json::Value::String(
                                serde_json::to_string(v).unwrap_or_else(|_| v.to_string()),
                            )
                        })
                        .collect(),
                )
            }
        }
        other => other,
    }
}
```

### 4. Replace the result handler block (lines ~313-337)

Collapse the entire output phase into a single `async` block returning `CliClientResult<()>`. JSON is always written to stdout **first** so that jq pipelines and callers always receive the API response. The TOML file write is advisory — it happens after stdout, and a failure still sets a non-zero exit code. This lets `?` propagate all output errors — TOML serialize, file write, JSON serialize — to the same `Err(e)` arm.

Note: since JSON is printed before the TOML path runs, `value` can be consumed by `strip_nulls` without cloning. The pipeline is `strip_nulls` → `homogenize_arrays` → `toml::to_string_pretty`. All file I/O uses `tokio::fs` to avoid blocking a Tokio worker thread.

```rust
let output_result: CliClientResult<()> = async {
    let value = result?;

    // Always emit JSON to stdout first — stdout always receives the API response.
    // jq pipelines remain unaffected even if the subsequent file write fails.
    let json = if cli.pretty {
        serde_json::to_string_pretty(&value).map_err(ClientError::from_json)?
    } else {
        serde_json::to_string(&value).map_err(ClientError::from_json)?
    };
    println!("{}", json);

    // Then attempt the optional TOML file write. Failure returns non-zero exit
    // but does not suppress the JSON already written to stdout.
    if let Some(toml_path) = &cli.output_toml {
        let cleaned = homogenize_arrays(strip_nulls(value));
        let content = toml::to_string_pretty(&cleaned).map_err(ClientError::from_toml_ser)?;
        tokio::fs::write(toml_path, content).await.map_err(ClientError::from_io)?;
    }

    Ok(())
}
.await;

match output_result {
    Ok(()) => ExitCode::SUCCESS,
    Err(e) => {
        eprintln!("Error: {}", e);
        ExitCode::FAILURE
    }
}
```

