## Context

With `WorkItemToml` defined and `Create` accepting optional fields, we wire up the merge logic. When `--from-toml` is set, we read and parse the TOML file as the base, then apply any CLI flags on top — CLI always wins. After merging we validate the type value (while still `Option`, before the required-fields check), then validate the three required fields individually so the error message names only what is actually missing.

All errors — I/O, TOML parse, missing fields, invalid type value — propagate as `ClientError` variants through the existing `Result`-based error handler in `main`. No inline `eprintln!` in the command arm.

**Important:** `async fn main() -> ExitCode` returns `ExitCode`, **not** `Result`. The `?` operator and `return Err(...)` only work inside a context that returns `Result`. To use both inside the `Create` arm, wrap the entire arm body in `async { ... }.await`. Inside that nested async block `?` propagates to the block's `CliClientResult<Value>`, not to `main()`. This is the same pattern used by the output-phase handler in PONE-213.

**Prerequisite:** PONE-211 must be completed first (adds `toml = { workspace = true }` to `pm-cli/Cargo.toml`). `load_work_item_toml` uses `toml::from_str` which requires that crate.

## Implementation

### 1. Extend ClientError in `backend/crates/pm-cli/src/client/error.rs`

Add two new variants. `TomlParse` carries the underlying `toml::de::Error` as a `#[source]` for error chain reporting. `Validation` is a user-facing error with no source (the input simply does not meet requirements; there is no underlying library error to chain).

```rust
#[error("TOML parse error: {message} {location}")]
TomlParse {
    message: String,
    location: ErrorLocation,
    #[source]
    source: toml::de::Error,
},

#[error("{message}")]
Validation {
    message: String,
},
```

Add a constructor alongside the existing `from_io`, `from_json`, etc.:

```rust
/// Convert a TOML deserialization error with context
#[track_caller]
pub fn from_toml(err: toml::de::Error) -> Self {
    ClientError::TomlParse {
        message: err.to_string(),
        location: ErrorLocation::from(Location::caller()),
        source: err,
    }
}
```

Add a `From` impl so `?` can coerce `toml::de::Error` into `ClientError`:

```rust
impl From<toml::de::Error> for ClientError {
    #[track_caller]
    fn from(err: toml::de::Error) -> Self {
        ClientError::from_toml(err)
    }
}
```

### 2. Add load_work_item_toml helper in `backend/crates/pm-cli/src/main.rs`

Returns `CliClientResult<WorkItemToml>` so both I/O and parse errors propagate via `?` in the Create arm, reaching the existing single error handler at the bottom of `main`. Must be `async` because it is called from within `#[tokio::main]`; using `std::fs` here would block a Tokio worker thread.

```rust
async fn load_work_item_toml(path: &str) -> CliClientResult<work_item_commands::WorkItemToml> {
    let content = tokio::fs::read_to_string(path)
        .await
        .map_err(ClientError::from_io)?;
    toml::from_str(&content).map_err(ClientError::from_toml)
}
```

### 3. Replace the WorkItemCommands::Create arm in `main.rs`

Wrap the entire arm body in `async { ... }.await`. This is required because `async fn main() -> ExitCode` returns `ExitCode` — `?` and `return Err(...)` cannot appear directly in its body unless the return type is `Result`. Inside the nested `async` block both operators propagate to the block's `CliClientResult<Value>`, which is then `.await`-ed and returned as the arm's value for the outer result handler.

Key ordering decision: the type-value validation (`if let Some(ref t) = item_type`) runs **before** the required-fields check, while `item_type` is still `Option`. This keeps the `if let` live on the `None` branch (skips validation when absent), and correctly intercepts invalid TOML-sourced values before the required-fields gate. The CLI `--type` flag enforces the allowed set via `value_parser`, but TOML-sourced values bypass clap's validation — an invalid `type = "foobar"` in a TOML file would otherwise reach the server and return a generic API error.

After the required-fields check all three fields are guaranteed `Some`; the `.unwrap()` calls are guarded. All errors surface through `Err(ClientError::Validation { ... })` and are printed by the existing `match result { Err(e) => eprintln!("Error: {}", e) }` handler consistently with all other errors.

```rust
WorkItemCommands::Create {
    project_id, r#type, title,
    description, parent_id, status, priority, from_toml,
} => {
    async {
        let base = if let Some(ref path) = from_toml {
            load_work_item_toml(path).await?  // OK — propagates inside async block, not main()
        } else {
            work_item_commands::WorkItemToml::default()
        };

        // CLI flags take precedence over TOML values
        let project_id  = project_id.or(base.project_id);
        let item_type   = r#type.or(base.item_type);
        let title       = title.or(base.title);
        let description = description.or(base.description);
        let parent_id   = parent_id.or(base.parent_id);
        let status      = status.or(base.status);
        let priority    = priority.or(base.priority);

        // Validate item_type value when present — TOML bypasses clap's value_parser constraint.
        // Runs before the required-fields check so item_type is still Option here;
        // the if let correctly skips when None.
        if let Some(ref t) = item_type {
            if !["epic", "story", "task"].contains(&t.as_str()) {
                return Err(ClientError::Validation {  // OK inside async block
                    message: format!(
                        "--type must be 'epic', 'story', or 'task'. Got: '{}'", t
                    ),
                });
            }
        }

        // Validate required fields after merging — report only what's actually missing
        let mut missing = vec![];
        if project_id.is_none() { missing.push("--project-id"); }
        if item_type.is_none()  { missing.push("--type"); }
        if title.is_none()      { missing.push("--title"); }
        if !missing.is_empty() {
            return Err(ClientError::Validation {  // OK inside async block
                message: format!(
                    "{} required. Provide via CLI flags or include in the --from-toml file.",
                    missing.join(", ")
                ),
            });
        }

        // Safe: all three guaranteed Some by required-fields check above
        let (project_id, item_type, title) =
            (project_id.unwrap(), item_type.unwrap(), title.unwrap());

        client
            .create_work_item(
                &project_id, &item_type, &title,
                description.as_deref(), parent_id.as_deref(),
                status.as_deref(), priority.as_deref(),
            )
            .await
    }
    .await
}
```

